Good Evening - This message is from Paul Zinni, Superintendent of the King Philip Regional School District. Due to the impending snow storm, school will be canceled tomorrow, March 4, 2019. All afterschool activities at the middle school will be canceled for tomorrow. Afterschool activities scheduled for 4PM or later at the King Philip Regional High School will occur as scheduled. Thank you and be safe.

Paul Zinni

post_text:
King Philip High School is one of only 35 schools in MA to adopt the AP Capstone program in an effort to help students better prepare for their lives ahead. AP Capstone is a project-based course that allows students to research topics of their own choosing, both in teams as as individuals, helping them improve their independent research, collaborative teamwork and communications skills. It is a CollegeBoard.org program.

This year our student-driven selections have ranged from the value of art education to the role of economics in the opioid crisis and space mining. Learn more in the video below.

https://youtu.be/0aoEXEIQKTM

post_text: KP Leo Club and Wrentham Lions host 2017 Senior Citizen Christmas Party - Like most weekends, it is not uncommon to find King Philip students immersed in activities to benefit our communities. On Sunday December 10th, the @KingPhilipLeoClub, in partnership with other local organizations, assisted in the hosting of the annual Senior Christmas party, sponsored by the Wrentham Lions. The event included a festive meal, Christmas caroling and other entertainment. Approximately 20 Leos assisted in set up, decorations, serving the meals and clean up. This year, an estimated 115 seniors from Norfolk, Plainville or Wrentham attended the event. The Wrentham Lions are truly grateful to the KP Leo Club each year for their support.

post_text:
KP Drama & GAPS Presents Peter Pan - The Musical

For the first time in fifteen years, KP Drama & GAPS will perform a full musical on the stage of the Richard K Grady Theatre. Peter Pan, the musical which made Mary Martin, Capt. Hook and Neverland popular with children & adults for the past 63 years will be performed Dec. 8 - 10. Evening performances will be Dec. 8 & 9 beginning at 7 PM and matinee' performances will be Dec. 9 & 10 at 2 PM. Tickets are $15 for adults and $8 for senior citizens and children under 12. Reserved seating tickets are now available on-line at http://kingphiliphsdrama.seatyourself.biz/ and will be sold on-line through Wednesday, Dec. 6th. Tickets for unsold seats will be sold at the door beginning one hour prior to each performance. Proceeds from the performance will be donated to the Tri-Town Food Pantries. Please visit the KP Drama Web site at www.kingphilip.org/HSDrama for further information.

post_text:
King Philip Regional High School is experiencing a fantastic fall, and thus most of our teams are making a run for the state championship. As a result, we have run into a significant conflict with the World Language Induction Ceremony scheduled for tomorrow night.

Students mandated by the charter must participate in the induction or not be a member of the society. Many of our students have a playoff game or are under an MIAA mandate that states they must attend practice or they are not able to play in the playoff game. Thus we are moving the induction ceremony so that all students may participate and enjoy all of their successes both athletically and academically.

The World Language Induction Ceremony is scheduled for December 13th at 8:30 am in the King Philip High School Auditorium with a reception to follow. We thank you in advance for your patience and understanding.

Henry Carr was an Ambassador for 15-40 Connection and shared with people how important it is to detect cancer early. His commitment to our mission has inspired us to push to be in every school in Massachusetts within the next few years. Our 3 Steps Detect education can be used by people of all ages and harnesses the power of patient insight to improve cancer survival rates. Our education teaches people how to set benchmarks for their health, when to act on changes and how to work proactively with healthcare providers to get to an accurate diagnosis.

Please join us at King Phillips High School on November 16th at 7 pm to learn how to detect cancer early.

Hear how 15-40 Connection impacted Henry at the link below.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ga0RzJ5LVGk

The King Philip DECA chapter is proud to announce for the sixth straight year, our chapter has returned from DECA's International Career Development Conference in Anaheim as International Champions. Three of our teams were announced as International DECA Finalist and two of our three teams make the top 10 and have become DECA Champions. Our entire chapter is proud of our delegation's confidence, preparation, and work ethic of all of our teams. Our organization is excited and optimistic about our future and anticipated success. Attached please find a few pictures. The following teams that made the international stage is listed below.
-Grace Patenaude (second year in a row) and Lillian Andrews in Fashion Promotion Plan, Top 16 internationally
-Nick Sammarco and Nick Simmons in Sports and Entertainment Promotion, Top 10 internationally
-Meghan Piller, Katherine Tobichuk, and Taylor Peterson in Learn and Earn, Top 10 internationally

post_text: On Saturday, April 29th at 12:00 there is going to be a field dedication ceremony at KPHS. The baseball field is going to be named in honor of Gary Lombard who was a teacher, guidance counselor and coach for many years in the KP school system. It will also be a celebration of his career. There will be a dedication ceremony with various speakers followed by a reception with refreshments in the Media Center. After the reception, KP will be playing Stoughton in baseball. We will also have a variety of memorabilia on display from Gary's career.

post_text: Last weekend, 19 members of KP’s Model United Nations delegation joined over 300 students from 20 different schools at UMass MUN XVI, the 16th annual Model United Nations Conference hosted by the University of Massachusetts Amherst. I’m thrilled to announce that our team won the award for Best Large Delegation, edging out some of the most competitive and experienced teams in the area. This award reflects not only the countless hours of hard work that our students put in over the last two months to prepare for the conference, but also the excellent education and support that they receive from every member of our community. The conference staff was particularly impressed by our team’s professionalism, enthusiasm, and positive attitude.
